{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528352"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:41:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:41:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14292"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14292"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.05,0.21,0.22,0.44]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6987"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109882"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6987"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14292"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92243"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"93"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16525"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41215"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46084"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109882"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a 24-hour history of gradual onset lower abdominal pain and diarrhoea. The pain is constant in nature and this is his fourth such episode in the last few months, with each episode resolving spontaneously after a few days. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He does not smoke and drinks alcohol occasionally on weekends.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 98/min, blood pressure 104/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft and not distended, with tenderness in the suprapubic region. A CT scan is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute appendicitis","Giardiasis","Diverticulitis","Pelvic abscess","Crohn\u0027s disease"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis young man presents with recurrent episodes of abdominal pain and diarrhoea, with CT findings showing terminal ileal wall thickening, which is highly suggestive of inflammatory bowel disease. \u003Cstrong\u003ECrohn\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents in young adults with episodic abdominal pain, diarrhoea, and systemic symptoms such as fever. The CT findings of bowel wall thickening particularly affecting the terminal ileum, together with surrounding fat stranding are characteristic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute appendicitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with migration of pain to the right iliac fossa, anorexia, and progressive worsening over 24-48 hours. The recurrent nature of symptoms and the CT findings make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGiardiasis\u003C/strong\u003E, caused by the parasite \u003Cem\u003EGiardia lamblia\u003C/em\u003E, typically causes chronic diarrhoea, bloating, and malabsorption. While it can cause recurrent symptoms, it would not cause the bowel wall thickening seen on CT, nor would it typically cause fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiverticulitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects older adults and usually involves the sigmoid colon rather than the terminal ileum. The patient is too young for this to be a likely diagnosis, and the location of pathology is incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPelvic abscess\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with more severe systemic symptoms and would appear as a fluid collection with rim enhancement on CT, rather than bowel wall thickening. While abscesses can complicate Crohn\u0027s disease, there is no evidence of abscess formation in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of Crohn\u0027s disease would be confirmed with colonoscopy and biopsy. Treatment options include anti-inflammatory medications, immunosuppressants such as azathioprine, and biologics depending on disease severity and extent.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Recurrent episodes of abdominal pain with diarrhoea in a young adult should raise suspicion for inflammatory bowel disease.","CT findings of bowel wall thickening, particularly in the terminal ileum, are characteristic of Crohn\u0027s disease.","The presence of fever suggests active inflammation rather than functional bowel disease."],"references":["Dolinger M, Torres J. Vermeire S. Crohn\u2019s disease. Lancet 2024 23; 403:1177-91","Sharma R. Crohn disease [Internet]. Radiopaedia. Radiopaedia.org; 2024. Available from: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/crohn-disease-2"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92243"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14292"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21074"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21074"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/qWvIGwPbqUQrhy9VCzv5nkdZ5FPimy.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/qWvIGwPbqUQrhy9VCzv5